(31, 30, 'This New Material Makes Things â€˜Invisibleâ€™ To Touch!', 'http://www.mairovergara.com/aprendendo-ingles-com-videos-030-this-new-material-makes-things-invisible-to-touch/', 'https://youtu.be/GJ5LlwqVN8A', 'This New Material Makes Things â€˜Invisibleâ€™ To Touch!\r\n\r\nGerman scientists have invented a material that can conceal any object known to man. This will only be used for goodâ€¦ I hope. Oh God, whatâ€™ve we done?\r\n\r\nHey guys, Tara here for Dnews â€“ and if it isnâ€™t obvious already, the future is amazing. We have self-driving cars, we have robots that can dance and sing. But you know what we donâ€™t have enough of? Invisibility cloaks. Oh, wait, just kidding â€“ we just invented one.\r\n\r\nThe fine people over at the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology in Germany have created a polymer that can make any object invisible to the sense of touch. So, when you lay it over something, it perfectly adapts and absorbs the shape of whateverâ€™s underneath it. This example photo shows a tiny metal cylinder encased in this polymer â€“ so, no matter how hard you press down on it, you wonâ€™t be able to feel the cylinder underneath.\r\n\r\nThe polymer itself consists of a bunch of tiny needle-shaped cones, whose tips meet to form a crystalline structure that encases an object and makes it completely impervious to detection. Even a force feedback mechanism wonâ€™t be able to determine the object hidden underneath. Whatâ€™s even cooler, is that each of those tiny cones is constructed with sub-micrometer accuracy. So, by changing the size of the contact points, you can theoretically create a material with any kind of mechanical properties you want, even those not found in nature. The researchers who invented this say it was developed purely for experimental purposes, but it does open up ideas for some interesting new applications.\r\n\r\nOne example they give â€“ that I could totally see myself using â€“ is for camping. If you created a very thin mattress out of this meta-material, it could completely absorb all of the twigs and jagged rocks underneath it. So, youâ€™d have a completely smooth surface, with no indication you were even sleeping on the ground. Of course, this is brand new â€“ so practical applications are still a long way off. But still! Just think of all the things we could do with this! Iâ€™m sure you guys have some awesome suggestions yourselves. So, as long as they donâ€™t involve couch cushions and several kilos of cocaine, feel free to share them!\r\n\r\nJust leave them in the comments below, or you can hit me up on Twitter at @TaraLongest.\r\n\r\nThat is all for me, but as always â€“ thank you guys for watching!', 'Este Novo Material Torna As Coisas â€œInvisÃ­veisâ€ Ao Toque!\r\n\r\nCientistas alemÃ£es inventaram um material que pode esconder qualquer objeto conhecido pelo homem. Isso serÃ¡ usado somente para o bemâ€¦ Eu espero. Ai Deus, o que nÃ³s fizemos?\r\n\r\nE aÃ­ pessoal, Tara aqui para o Dnews â€“ e se isso ainda nÃ£o Ã© Ã³bvio, o futuro Ã© incrÃ­vel. NÃ³s temos carros auto dirigÃ­veis, nÃ³s temos robÃ´s que podem danÃ§ar e cantar. Mas vocÃª sabe o que nÃ³s nÃ£o temos ainda? Capas de invisibilidade. Espere aÃ­, brincadeira â€“ nÃ³s acabamos de inventar uma.\r\n\r\nAs boas pessoas lÃ¡ do Instituto Karlsruhe de Tecnologia na Alemanha criaram um polÃ­mero que pode fazer qualquer objeto invisÃ­vel ao sentido do toque. EntÃ£o, quando vocÃª o coloca sobre alguma coisa, ele se adapta perfeitamente e absorve o formato do que estiver embaixo dele. Essa foto de exemplo mostra um cilindro minÃºsculo de metal envolto nesse polÃ­mero â€“ entÃ£o, nÃ£o importa o quÃ£o forte vocÃª o pressiona para baixo, vocÃª nÃ£o conseguirÃ¡ sentir o cilindro embaixo.\r\n\r\nO polÃ­mero em si consiste de um grupo de minÃºsculos cones em formato de agulha, cujas pontas se encontram para formar uma estrutura cristalina que reveste um objeto e faz com que ele seja completamente insensÃ­vel Ã  detecÃ§Ã£o. Mesmo um mecanismo d